                    <physDesc>
                        <objectDesc>
                            <supportDesc>
                                <support><p><ref target="https://www.archaeology.ie/archaeological-survey-ireland/historic-environment-viewer-application">National Monuments Service</ref> SMR ID: <idno type="HER">KK024-062005-</idno></p>
                                    <material type="stone">Grit</material> 
                                    <objectType key="monument">Pillar</objectType>                                     
                                    <dimensions unit="m" source="MAC1945">                                         
                                            <height>0.70</height>
                                            <width>0.51</width>
                                            <depth>0.27</depth>
                                        <!--<dim type="diameter">if circular, etc</dim>-->
                                     </dimensions>         
                                </support>
                                <condition>The stump of a pillar stone, the top of the stone is broken off and lost (Macalister 1945, 39-40). All that remains of the ogham inscription is less than three letters and what remains is much clogged with lichen (Macalister 1945 40). There is also a distinctive cut on the face of the stone which Macalister (1945, 40) dismisses as <q>an oblique mark of no importance</q>. However, it bears some resemblance to those found on (I-KER-075) Kilcoolaght East I, Co. Kerry; Ratass, Co. Kerry (described as being used as <q>a sharpening stone for knives and other blades</q>); Church Island, Co. Kerry (used for sharpening <q>some broad bladed implement</q>); (I-COR-003) Greenhill I, Co. Cork, where they have been described as <q>hone scores</q> and to another on (I-KID-001) Colbinstown I, Co. Kildare which has been described as <q>a blade mark</q> (Newman 2009, 433-4). </condition>
                            </supportDesc>
                            <layoutDesc>
                                <layout style="vertical" rend="arris-up">Macalister (1945, 39) maintains that the inscription was on two angles of the stone and read up-top-down.</layout>
                            </layoutDesc>
                        </objectDesc>
                        <handDesc>
                            <handNote>The ogham letters are <rs type="execution"  key="pocked" ref="https://www.eagle-network.eu/voc/writing/lod/11.html">pocked</rs> in broad short scores. 
                            </handNote>
                        </handDesc>
                    </physDesc>
